<div id="review_157317493" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/157317493" />
    <a title="Jasmine" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1122151-jasmine"><img alt="Jasmine" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1616125477p2/1122151.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/157317493?book_show_action=true">Mar 28, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jasmine" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jasmine" href="/user/show/1122151-jasmine">Jasmine</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9781906694975" href="/book/show/8928842-love-virtually">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1122151-jasmine?shelf=austrian">austrian</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer157317493" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11266969782380596348">So this book is a bit like vox for the net millennium. I have a weird relationship to this book. <br/><br/>basically the guy that I currently have a &quot;relationship&quot; with is a guy I&apos;ve known for 6 years online. we hung out years ago in the same forum. I know people in real life that have met him in real life. we both know people online that have met the other in real life. he&apos;s been to new york, for all we know in the same room as me. basically the internet is a very complicated network of people who intera</span>
  <span id="freeText11266969782380596348" style="display:none">So this book is a bit like vox for the net millennium. I have a weird relationship to this book. <br /><br />basically the guy that I currently have a "relationship" with is a guy I've known for 6 years online. we hung out years ago in the same forum. I know people in real life that have met him in real life. we both know people online that have met the other in real life. he's been to new york, for all we know in the same room as me. basically the internet is a very complicated network of people who interact on all different kinds of levels. I have to say as part of the tech savvy youth, I am commonly texting, emailing and iming within a group of 3 or 4 people, most of whom are using more than one method of communication.<br /><br />for example currently. David: text, im, forum. Dave: im, forum. Pix: im. Kennedy: forum. you're getting the picture. basically tech interaction in surround sound. <br /><br />On the other hand I think I've made it abundantly clear that I am a huge fan of the epistolary novel. so bringing these things together works for me. <br /><br />I don't know on the other hand if these things coming together would work for people who aren't really part of that world. I mean I think my mom would just be confused how they even met online. I mean a mistaken email... (this happens in matt beaumont too! it's a theme). I think this novel is a very direct thing that you have to understand from a specific view of the world. <br /><br />basically I'm just standing in the exact right position to enjoy this novel. Plus I love language psychology. <br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ and I am so fucking glad they didn't meet. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br /><br />————————————2020 update <br />On the review: <br />David is married. <br /><br />I can’t tell from what I wrote here if I wrote this review before, during or after we dated. Probably not after since I didn’t mention meeting. <br /><br />On the book: <br />The parts of this book that are different as I’ve gotten older are the moments about disillusionment. The idea that meeting is the thing that ruins everything for people who exist online. That “loving someone’s words” doesn’t translate to real life in most cases. That there are fundamental incompatibilities that don’t exist inside who we are online. That our insecurities and problems are not there. <br /><br />This book scratches the surface of that. Something is wrong in Emmi’s life no matter how perfect she tells herself it is. Something is wrong not because she’s talking to someone online but because of what she’s trying to get from that person. <br /><br />I don’t know how much I picked up on the creeping discontent from Emmi’s side or the growing hopelessness from Leo’s side. But now being the same age as the characters I think I understand them more than I did at 25? I mean that would likely have been before I was in a 4 year relationship that was “perfect” except for the fact that it barely existed. I have a much more nuanced understanding of a perfect relationship and maybe more I can layer on top of Emmi’s personal “perfect marriage” to build meaning for myself in the book. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="11266969782380596348" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


