  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_996044603" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/996044603" />
    <a title="Ananya" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2787475-ananya"><img alt="Ananya" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1374162782p2/2787475.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/996044603?book_show_action=true">Jul 14, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ananya" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ananya" href="/user/show/2787475-ananya">Ananya</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9781906694975" href="/book/show/8928842-love-virtually">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer996044603" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12170149631609489590"><p> I spotted this unusual hardbound book in the library searching for the perfect holiday read. Since I had another book in mind and I had issued it already, I decided to read a couple of pages instead. First two pages and I was hooked. Unfortunately I had to stop there since I&apos;d to hurry home. As soon as i finished the one I issued, I came searching for this utterly attractive book and to my disappointment, couldn&apos;t find it. Incidentally I&apos;d managed to forget this remarkable book&apos;s name. I ask th</p></span>
  <span id="freeText12170149631609489590" style="display:none"><p> I spotted this unusual hardbound book in the library searching for the perfect holiday read. Since I had another book in mind and I had issued it already, I decided to read a couple of pages instead. First two pages and I was hooked. Unfortunately I had to stop there since I'd to hurry home. As soon as i finished the one I issued, I came searching for this utterly attractive book and to my disappointment, couldn't find it. Incidentally I'd managed to forget this remarkable book's name. I ask the librarian, "do you have a copy of "digital love?" She checks her database, politely refuses. For weeks I fail to locate it in the shelf where I had first seen it. Finally losing hope that if I find this book at all it'll be in another library, I take one book after another. One fateful day that is 13th June, I find my most sought after book exactly where I wanted to see it. I grab it, relish it, eat it, dream it.</p><br /><p>From the first page itself, I had rated this epistolary piece 5/5. It's everything it promises to be, 'funny, fast-paced, utterly absorbing, with plenty of twists and turns'. Moreover if you're a man, you might crave for a woman as bubbly and sarcastic as <i>Emmi</i> and if a woman with a penchant for enigmatic letters, you'll fall for <i>Leo</i>, so beautifully has their personality been outlined without a line from a third person. Their curiosity will become your own, entrapping you with their passion, fear and intrigue.</p><br /><p><u>Leo</u><br />I'll write about Leo first. Purely for the reason that I fell in love with him. He starts with such a minute analysis of Emmi's personality that however striking it may be to her, it struck me. The way he described his observation of her in cafe Huber, though it was his sister's brilliance, it left me awestruck for a moment. His pauses, his fluidity, his demeanor, his craving, his analysis, his secrecy, his openness, his sensitiveness, his passion, his concern, his charm... I can go on and on... have left me fantasizing, just like Emmi, how a man who writes like that, look like.</p><br /><p><u>Emmi</u><br />She's one woman I'd like to befriend, definitely if not intimately. She writes so much like I think I write. Her numbering points has... I don't know... I just get a smile on my face when she starts numbering her questions and points. Leo's impatience wasn't as projected as Emmi's and I could completely relate to it! I guess most women are like that, writing "arsehole" if they're expecting a reply and don't get it within a week!</p><br /><p>The best part is the English. I openly laud the translators for doing such a terrific work of translation. I couldn't find a single line or word sticking out and I hope (I know!) none of the colloquial humor was lost in the translation. Glattauer has done his part of impressive writing (as well as research/study of womens' n mens' psychology in letter/ email writing) and Bielenberg and Bulloch have done justice to his novel. (Does it take just one man to write a dialogue and two to translate?)<br />I was double excited when after turning the last page, I discover there's a sequel to it! I hope I get hold of it soon. In fact, I'm too curious to know myself how chatting with a sensible but anonymous stranger feel like. (Like, like, like! Leo.)</p></span>
  <a data-text-id="12170149631609489590" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


